An emulation of the 7406 hex inverter.

The 7406 is one of the 7400-series TTL logic chips, consisting of six single-input inverters. An inverter is the simplest of logic gates: if the input is low, the output is high, and vice versa.

AnYn
LH
HL

The chip comes in a 14-pin dual in-line package with the following pin assignments.

        +---+--+---+
     A1 |1  +--+ 14| Vcc
     Y1 |2       13| A6
     A2 |3       12| Y6
     Y2 |4  7406 11| A5
     A3 |5       10| Y5
     Y3 |6        9| A4
    GND |7        8| Y4
        +----------+
GND and Vcc are ground and power supply pins respectively, and they are not emulated.

In the Commodore 64, U8 is a 7406. It's responsible for inverting logic signals that are expected in the inverse they're given, such as the 6567's AEC signal being turned into the inverse AEC signal for the 82S100.
